<DocPage title="Protocol Overview">
  <h1>Protocol Overview</h1>

  <p>
    The TermSurf protocol is the most important artifact in the project. It
    defines how terminals, browser engines, and TUIs communicate over Unix
    sockets using length-prefixed protobuf messages.
  </p>

  <h2>Wire Format</h2>

  <p>
    Every message on the wire is a serialized <code>TermSurfMessage</code>
    protobuf, prefixed with a 4-byte little-endian length:
  </p>

  <pre class="bg-background-dark p-3 border-l-2 border-border text-foreground-dark text-xs mb-6 overflow-x-auto"><code>[4 bytes: length (LE u32)] [N bytes: serialized protobuf]</code></pre>

  <p>
    <code>TermSurfMessage</code> is a wrapper with a <code>oneof msg</code>
    field. Each message on the wire is exactly one variant.
  </p>

  <h2>Connections</h2>

  <p>
    The GUI (Ghostboard) listens on a PID-scoped Unix socket. Two types of
    clients connect:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>TUIs</strong> — discover the socket via the
      <code>TERMSURF_SOCKET</code> environment variable. Send overlay and
      navigation messages.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Browser engines</strong> — receive the socket path via
      <code>--ipc-socket=</code> command-line argument. Send registration and
      state updates.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The GUI identifies the connection type from the first message:
    <code>ServerRegister</code> means browser engine, anything else means TUI.
  </p>

  <h2>Message Categories</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Category</th>
        <th>Direction</th>
        <th>Messages</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Tab lifecycle</td>
        <td>GUI &rarr; Engine</td>
        <td>CreateTab, CreateDevtoolsTab, Resize, CloseTab</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Navigation</td>
        <td>TUI &rarr; GUI, GUI &rarr; Engine</td>
        <td>Navigate</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Input</td>
        <td>GUI &rarr; Engine</td>
        <td>MouseEvent, MouseMove, ScrollEvent, KeyEvent</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>State</td>
        <td>GUI &rarr; Engine</td>
        <td>FocusChanged, SetColorScheme</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Engine events</td>
        <td>Engine &rarr; GUI</td>
        <td>ServerRegister, TabReady, CaContext, UrlChanged, LoadingState, TitleChanged, CursorChanged, TargetUrlChanged</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Overlay</td>
        <td>TUI &rarr; GUI</td>
        <td>SetOverlay, SetDevtoolsOverlay, OpenSplit</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Mode sync</td>
        <td>TUI &harr; GUI</td>
        <td>ModeChanged</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Direct connection</td>
        <td>GUI &rarr; TUI</td>
        <td>BrowserReady</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Request/reply</td>
        <td>TUI &harr; GUI</td>
        <td>Hello, QueryLast, QueryDevtools, QueryTabs</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Message Flow</h2>

  <p>A typical session when a user types <code>web example.com</code>:</p>

  <ol>
    <li>TUI connects to GUI socket</li>
    <li>TUI sends <code>HelloRequest</code> &rarr; GUI replies <code>HelloReply</code></li>
    <li>TUI sends <code>SetOverlay</code> with URL, profile, pane dimensions</li>
    <li>GUI spawns browser engine (if not already running for this profile)</li>
    <li>Engine connects, sends <code>ServerRegister</code></li>
    <li>GUI sends <code>CreateTab</code> to engine</li>
    <li>Engine creates WebContents, sends <code>TabReady</code></li>
    <li>GUI sends <code>BrowserReady</code> to TUI (with engine's listen socket)</li>
    <li>TUI connects directly to engine for navigation</li>
    <li>Engine renders, sends <code>CaContext</code> (GPU layer ID)</li>
    <li>GUI creates <code>CALayerHost</code> overlay &mdash; browser appears in pane</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Direct Browser Connection</h2>

  <p>
    After initialization, the TUI can send <code>Navigate</code> and
    <code>SetColorScheme</code> directly to the browser engine, bypassing the
    GUI. The engine also listens on its own socket (passed via
    <code>--listen-socket=</code>). The GUI provides this path to the TUI in
    the <code>BrowserReady</code> message.
  </p>

  <h2>Serialization</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rust</strong> (GUI, TUI, engines) &mdash; prost</li>
    <li><strong>C++</strong> (Chromium) &mdash; protobuf</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The protocol is defined in <code>proto/termsurf.proto</code>. See
    <a href="/docs/protocol/messages">Messages</a> for the full reference.
  </p>
</DocPage>
